tList of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of essays examines social, political, and economic relations in primarily European coastal locations through the lens of tourism. The contributors explore the intersecting interests of fishing, tourism, and development and the conflict among local communities and market forces, all of which are infused with the symbolism of the sea as a place of mystery and danger. From the tensions between Cornish villagers and city visitors to the explosion of resort development in Gran Canaria, the authors consider the relationship between local residents, businesses, and tourist newcomers as they vie for status, influence, and, ultimately, for space.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCoastal zone management. 0aCulture and tourism. 0aSustainable development. 0aTourism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAlban, Frédérique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBianchi, Raoul V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoissevain, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoissevain, Jeremy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoncoeur, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClifton, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuim, René van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrangoudes, Katia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIreland, Michael John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKousis, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLengkeek, Jaap, econtributor.